<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="484" type="nomenclature">
Family 
<taxonomicName box="[481,839,611,678]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">ATELIDAE</taxonomicName>
(HOWLERS, SPIDER AND WOOLLY MONKEYS AND MURIQUIS)
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="484" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[1232,2110,841,1036]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">• Medium-sized to large monkeys with long limbs or shorter limbs and more robust, howlers with enlarged voice-box and head set low on shoulders (hunched), dense and woolly or long and coarse fur, and long, strong, prehensile tail.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[1232,1572,1039,1272]" box="[1232,1439,1039,1077]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">
• 
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6585326" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6585326" box="[1269,1439,1039,1077]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6585326/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" startId="0.[1269,1308,1039,1077]" targetBox="[1566,1852,1051,1269]" targetPageId="0">80-160 cm.</caption>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[1232,1572,1039,1272]" lastBlockId="0.[1232,2111,1283,1470]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">
• 
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6585330" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6585330" box="[1269,1572,1239,1272]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6585330/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" startId="0.[1269,1450,1239,1272]" targetBox="[225,1160,854,1474]" targetPageId="0">Neotropical Region</caption>
• Humid, lowland, submontane and montane, deciduous, and semi-deciduous forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="484" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[1232,2111,1283,1470]" box="[1233,1705,1353,1391]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">• 5 genera, 25 species, 42 taxa.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[1232,2111,1283,1470]" lastBlockId="0.[164,1132,1691,3470]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">
• 4 species Critically Endangered, 8 species Endangered, 5 species Vulnerable; none Extinct since 1600 Systematics The species of 
<taxonomicName box="[398,524,1691,1724]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Atelidae</taxonomicName>
are the largest of the New World monkeys. They are a distinct monophyletic clade of five genera and 25 species, all with prehensile tails and ranging in size from 3 kg (females of the diminutive “Coiba Island Howler,” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1849" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="532" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="palliata">Alouatta palliata</taxonomicName>
coibensis) to the muriquis (
<taxonomicName box="[700,852,1857,1890]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Brachyteles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Brachyteles</taxonomicName>
) in south-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[171,259,1898,1931]" name="Brazil" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, which can reach 11-12 kg. They occur throughout the American tropics. The “Mexican Spider Monkey” (
<taxonomicName box="[928,1009,1939,1972]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Ateles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ateles</taxonomicName>
geoffroy: vellerosus) is the northernmost of the platyrrhines, occurring in lowland, montane, evergreen, and dry forests of Veracruz State just north of the Tropic of Cancer, and the “Southern Brown Howler” (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Humboldt" authorityYear="1812" box="[325,570,2109,2138]" class="Mammalia" family="Atelidae" genus="Alouatta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="guariba">Alouatta guariba</taxonomicName>
clamitans) is the southernmost, extending some distance south of the Tropic of Capricorn to 31° S, where seasonal semi-deciduous Atlantic Forest gives way to the Pampas of 
<taxonomicName box="[396,550,2230,2263]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Argentina" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<collectingCountry box="[396,550,2230,2263]" name="Argentina" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">Argentina</collectingCountry>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[628,760,2230,2263]" name="Uruguay" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
